<item>
            <title>[SPR-1370] SimpleUrlHandlerMapping returns 404 when requestURI equals contextPath</title>
                <link>https://jira.spring.io/browse/SPR-1370</link>
                <project id="10000" key="SPR">Spring Framework</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;I have a webapp configured for the path /redimo and a servlet-mapping in web.xml for the url-pattern &apos;/*&apos; to a DispatcherServlet&lt;br/&gt;
I use a SimpleUrlHandlerMapping to map the path &apos;/&apos; to a controller.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This causes the controller to be invoked when i access &lt;a href=&quot;http://localhost:8080/redimo/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://localhost:8080/redimo/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
When I invoke the same url without a trailing slash (&lt;a href=&quot;http://localhost:8080/redimo&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://localhost:8080/redimo&lt;/a&gt;) , I&apos;ll get a 404 &apos;the requested resource not available&apos; error from the DispatcherServlet. This is because the request methods getContextPath() and getRequestURI() returns the same string, so UrlPathHelper.getPathWithinApplication() returns &quot;&quot; which can per definition never match a controller since SimpleUrlHandlerMapping always contains at least &apos;/&apos;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When you have your spring application configured as the ROOT webapp at least tomcat solves this problem by redirecting &lt;a href=&quot;http://localhost:8080&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://localhost:8080&lt;/a&gt; to &lt;a href=&quot;http://localhost:8080/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://localhost:8080/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
